# AGENTS.md — clawpm task tracking

> **For agent runtimes that read `AGENTS.md` (Codex, etc.) — copy this file into your project root and customize the project ID and portfolio path. For Claude Code projects, the canonical equivalent is `CLAUDE.md` and the `clawpm` skill auto-loads.**

This project uses [`clawpm`](https://github.com/martinduncanson/clawpm) for task tracking and work-log persistence across agent sessions. Use it preferentially over session-scoped TODO lists. (Forked from upstream [`malphas-gh/clawpm`](https://github.com/malphas-gh/clawpm).)

## Why

Session-scoped task tools (whatever your runtime calls them) disappear when the session ends. clawpm persists tasks, work logs, research notes, and issues to the filesystem — they survive session boundaries, agent handoffs, and subagent dispatch.

## Project context

- **Project ID:** `<REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>` (matches `.project/settings.toml` `id` field)
- **Portfolio:** `~/clawpm/` (override with `CLAWPM_PORTFOLIO` env var)
- **Settings file:** `<repo-root>/.project/settings.toml`

## Invocation patterns

```bash
# Resume work — read this first when starting any session
clawpm context --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>

# Add a task
clawpm tasks add --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID> -t "Title" -b "Description" \
    --predict-duration 60 --predict-complexity m \
    --predict-scope "src/foo/**" --hypothesis "if X then Y"

# Start working
clawpm start <task-id> --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>

# Pre-flight check before dispatching parallel agents
clawpm conflicts --task <task-id> --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>

# Complete with reflection
clawpm done <task-id> --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID> \
    --note "what shipped" \
    --reflect-note "what surprised me" \
    --meta-reflect "what could have been anticipated that wasn't"

# Block on dependency
clawpm block <task-id> --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID> --note "Waiting on credentials"

# Log progress without state change
clawpm log add --task <task-id> --action progress --summary "What I did" --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>

# Session orientation — Claude-rendered 2-paragraph briefing (CLAWP-025)
clawpm resume --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>

# Reference-class anchoring at predict time (CLAWP-023) — tasks add emits
# `suggested_references` in the response when --reference-task isn't pinned
# AND predictions are set. Look at the prior actuals before committing to
# your duration estimate.

# Parent-spawned subagent dispatch with rubric enforcement (CLAWP-024)
clawpm agent dispatch --prompt "do X" \
    --rubric-criteria "evidence Y in transcript" \
    --rubric-criteria "no regression in Z" \
    --parent <task-id> --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>

# Mission Control — 4-week binary outcome above tasks (CLAWP-022)
clawpm mission add --title "Ship X" --binary-outcome "X in prod" \
    --deadline-days 28 --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>
clawpm mission add-goal <MISSION-ID> --task <task-id> --actor agent
clawpm mission status <MISSION-ID> --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>

# Auto-remediation of doctor warnings (CLAWP-026)
clawpm doctor --apply --yes --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>
clawpm doctor --apply --dry-run --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>  # preview
```

## Agentic layer — plan, dispatch, verify

The planner skill plans on a capable model; the deterministic core persists and dispatches; cheap models execute under an enforced rubric. See the README for the full loop.

```bash
# Persist a fully-contracted task-tree atomically — zero LLM calls (planner emits this)
clawpm tasks emit-tree --project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID> [--dry-run] [--strict] < tree.json

# Render a task's success-criteria as a gradeable rubric
clawpm tasks emit-rubric <task-id> [--rubric-format markdown]

# Dispatch a leaf — writes hook-wired .claude/settings.local.json (Stop-hook rubric gate)
clawpm tasks dispatch <task-id> [--worktree] [--confirm-close] [--refute-votes N] \
    [--lease-ttl <secs>] \
    [--fallback-policy requeue|route-secondary|escalate-to-human|fail] [--confirm-stale]
clawpm tasks teardown-dispatch <task-id>       # remove the dispatch settings

# Stop-hook judge — the subagent cannot terminate until its rubric is satisfied
clawpm hook eval-stop --task <task-id>

# Crash-safe leases: TTL + heartbeat + lazy expiry (no daemon)
clawpm lease grant --task <task-id> --ttl <secs> --fallback-policy <p>
clawpm lease heartbeat --task <task-id>
clawpm lease list [--project <REPLACE-WITH-PROJECT-ID>]
clawpm lease sweep [--dry-run]

# Comparative pairwise selection among candidate deliverables
clawpm judge tournament --rubric-file rubric.md \
    --candidate a.txt --candidate b.txt [--label v1] [--label v2]

# Decompose an existing task into child subtasks, each with its own rubric
clawpm tasks decompose <parent-id> --child "Title" \
    --child '{"title":"...","success_criteria":["..."],"complexity":"m"}'
```

## Tags, filters, and bulk state

```bash
# Cross-cutting workstream tags (CLAWP-069, repeatable, lowercased)
clawpm tasks add -t "..." --tag concurrency --tag mcp
clawpm tasks list --tag concurrency [--all-tags]      # repeated --tag = OR; --all-tags = AND
clawpm tasks tags                                     # distinct tags with counts

# Query filters + [[wiki-link]] backlinks (CLAWP-082)
clawpm tasks list --text "auth" [--regex] --priority "<=3" --complexity l --limit 10
clawpm tasks list --parent <task-id>                  # direct subtasks of a parent
clawpm tasks list --linked <task-id>                  # tasks referencing an id (wiki-link or typed edge)

# Bulk state (CLAWP-083): many IDs at once, per-task isolation, aggregate result
clawpm done 72 73 74 --note "batch complete"
clawpm start 72 73 74
```

## When to invoke

| Lifecycle moment | clawpm action |
|---|---|
| Session start | `clawpm resume` for orientation, then `clawpm context` for full state |
| Before any meaningful work unit (≥15 min) | `clawpm tasks add` with predictions — check `suggested_references` in the response for reference-class anchoring |
| Before dispatching parallel subagents | `clawpm conflicts --task` to verify safe scope; `clawpm next --batch` to find a dispatchable group |
| When spawning a subagent | `clawpm agent dispatch --prompt ... --rubric-criteria ...` — enforces rubric via Stop-hook judge |
| On completion | `clawpm done` with `--reflect-note` + `--process-lesson` |
| On blocker | `clawpm block --note` |
| Before commit | `clawpm log add --action progress --summary "what's about to commit"` |
| After commit | `clawpm log commit` to record the SHA against the task |
| Maintenance | `clawpm doctor --apply --dry-run` to preview auto-fixes, then `--apply --yes` to apply |
| Macro-experiment (4-week outcome) | `clawpm mission add` → `add-goal` per mini-goal → `mission status` for progress |
| Session end | `clawpm log tail --limit 5` to verify the trail is captured |

## Output format

clawpm emits JSON by default (`-f json`, default). Use `-f text` for human-readable output. Agents should consume JSON; humans get text.

## Failure modes

- **`add_failed`**: Settings.toml has Windows backslashes — fix to forward slashes (the CLI now warns about this).
- **`no_project`**: CWD walk found no `.project/settings.toml` — pass `--project <id>` explicitly or `cd` into the project root.
- **`portfolio_not_found`**: First-time setup needed — run `clawpm setup`.

